Jennifer has always said

00:01:38.464 --> 00:01:42.702
that I have this teenage crush

00:01:42.702 --> 00:01:44.870
about Papua New Guinea.

00:01:44.870 --> 00:01:47.473
But 18 years ago,
it's now 18 years ago,

00:01:47.473 --> 00:01:51.177
I was in a place
called Kimbe Bay,

00:01:51.177 --> 00:01:54.080
I was there for the
total of six days.

00:01:54.080 --> 00:01:55.648
And in those six days I made

00:01:55.648 --> 00:01:58.384
some very serious,
wonderful pictures.

00:01:58.718 --> 00:02:02.355
And I had to go back,
I had to go back.

00:02:02.355 --> 00:02:05.391
But the years passed
and suddenly...

00:02:05.391 --> 00:02:08.728
The phone
rang and it was...

00:02:08.728 --> 00:02:10.763
It was the office

00:02:10.763 --> 00:02:13.633
and they said to me,

00:02:13.633 --> 00:02:17.503
"You. You have been selected

00:02:17.503 --> 00:02:20.139
to participate, to contribute

00:02:20.139 --> 00:02:23.409
in the 125th anniversary issue,

00:02:23.409 --> 00:02:25.211
David: the photography issue

00:02:25.211 --> 00:02:27.413
of the<i> National
 Geographic magazine</i> ."

00:02:27.780 --> 00:02:31.283
They said, "You can
go anywhere you want,

00:02:31.283 --> 00:02:33.652
shoot anything you want."

00:02:33.652 --> 00:02:39.625
And I said to myself,
"Kimbe Bay," ding!

00:02:39.992 --> 00:02:42.395
And so we had an assignment.

00:02:42.862 --> 00:02:48.100
But here's a problem that
all of you share right now

00:02:48.100 --> 00:02:53.405
and that problem is 'Where
the hell is Kimbe Bay?'

00:02:53.405 --> 00:02:54.907
(audience laughter)

00:02:54.907 --> 00:02:57.910
David: Well, Kimbe Bay is in
the Coral Triangle.

00:02:57.910 --> 00:03:03.449
And the Coral Triangle
is where, on this planet,

00:03:03.449 --> 00:03:09.422
the most bio-diverse,
the most numbers

00:03:09.422 --> 00:03:13.426
of fish, coral and of
course, invertebrates live.

00:03:13.426 --> 00:03:15.461
This was a perfect assignment.

00:03:15.461 --> 00:03:19.232
What could possibly go wrong?

00:03:19.632 --> 00:03:21.100
Hmm.

00:03:21.901 --> 00:03:25.137 line:0%
The whole story's
had a cloud over it.

00:03:25.137 --> 00:03:27.440 line:0%
Boiling dark cloud.

00:03:27.440 --> 00:03:29.575
The monsoon is still going on.

00:03:29.575 --> 00:03:33.745
The wettest March
and April since 1970.

00:03:33.745 --> 00:03:37.049
The batteries are smoldering,
stinking and burning.

00:03:37.049 --> 00:03:38.952
Your camera's on fire.

00:03:38.952 --> 00:03:40.386
It nearly burnt the place down.

00:03:40.386 --> 00:03:41.754
Strobes flood.

00:03:41.754 --> 00:03:42.922
A GoPro floods.

00:03:42.922 --> 00:03:43.556
Gone.

00:03:43.689 --> 00:03:44.490
We lose another light.

00:03:44.791 --> 00:03:46.058
The electronics are scrambled.

00:03:46.058 --> 00:03:47.293
Torrential rains.

00:03:47.293 --> 00:03:48.127
And kaboom!

00:03:48.127 --> 00:03:49.328
Another $3,000.

00:03:49.328 --> 00:03:50.529
Charger blows up.

00:03:50.529 --> 00:03:55.634
Like this place
has it in for us.

00:03:55.634 --> 00:03:57.903
Mosquitoes are buzzing
around our heads.

00:03:57.903 --> 00:04:00.039
You don't have to
worry about the bends,

00:04:00.039 --> 00:04:01.573
you have malaria.

00:04:01.573 --> 00:04:03.676
And as of two days
ago, a cyclone.

00:04:03.676 --> 00:04:06.011
Guinea is eating us
up and spit us out.

00:04:06.011 --> 00:04:08.147
And this story was
supposed to be a gift,

00:04:08.147 --> 00:04:10.883
an easy, beautiful story.

00:04:10.883 --> 00:04:14.320
Funny, all these years,
all these stories,

00:04:14.320 --> 00:04:16.121
every place we've
gone to we're sort of

00:04:16.121 --> 00:04:17.390
reluctant to leave.

00:04:17.390 --> 00:04:19.592
But it's over now.

00:04:21.093 --> 00:04:23.061
So say goodnight Buffalo Bob.

00:04:23.061 --> 00:04:24.864
Goodnight Buffalo Bob.

00:04:25.398 --> 00:04:28.267
Well, the one sunny day.

00:04:29.067 --> 00:04:31.971
David: This is what this place
looked like.

00:04:31.971 --> 00:04:34.006
It's an absolute paradise.

00:04:34.006 --> 00:04:37.877
Deep water with these
wonderful sea mounds

00:04:37.877 --> 00:04:41.147
rising from thousands of
feet, almost to the surface,

00:04:41.147 --> 00:04:43.616
and surrounded by volcanoes.

00:04:44.450 --> 00:04:47.353
And here's this mysterious lake

00:04:47.353 --> 00:04:50.889
called Dok Toek,
the forbidden lake.

00:04:50.889 --> 00:04:53.893
No foreigners,
nobody but tribesmen

00:04:53.893 --> 00:04:57.029
can go to this lake because
it's full of spirits

00:04:57.029 --> 00:04:59.131
and crocodiles.

00:04:59.731 --> 00:05:03.002
The offshore reefs, like
this incredible place

00:05:03.002 --> 00:05:05.905
called Kimbe Bomi and
they were far offshore,

00:05:05.905 --> 00:05:08.107
two and a half hour
boat rides every day.

00:05:08.107 --> 00:05:11.044
Hundred and twenty-five feet
down at the top of the reef.

00:05:11.044 --> 00:05:13.379
They were like absolute gardens,

00:05:13.379 --> 00:05:17.016
these deep,
underwater volcanoes.

00:05:18.617 --> 00:05:20.753
♪ (melodic music) ♪

00:05:20.753 --> 00:05:23.422
David: Bradford is the most
spectacular dive here.

00:05:23.422 --> 00:05:26.091
There's a sea mount
called Bradford Shoals.

00:05:26.091 --> 00:05:28.161
It rises up from the deep,

00:05:28.161 --> 00:05:30.863
it is rounded, steep-shouldered

00:05:30.863 --> 00:05:35.435
and has an immense school
of chevron barracuda,

00:05:35.435 --> 00:05:37.603
which swim around
in great circles,

00:05:37.603 --> 00:05:39.871
almost making
funnel-shaped clouds.

00:05:39.871 --> 00:05:43.509
Around they go,
spooling upwards.

00:05:47.980 --> 00:05:50.850
When fish move in
a circular pattern,

00:05:50.850 --> 00:05:52.818
they create the
rarest thing in the sea

00:05:52.818 --> 00:05:54.954
which is a geometric pattern,

00:05:54.954 --> 00:05:57.756
a place that has no
corners, no edges.

00:05:57.756 --> 00:06:01.361
Geometry in a place
of weightless chaos.

00:06:02.494 --> 00:06:05.665
♪ (melodic music continues) ♪

00:06:08.267 --> 00:06:11.304
And then the barracudas
would form these immense,

00:06:11.304 --> 00:06:14.306
circular tornado-shaped towers,

00:06:14.306 --> 00:06:17.443
David: going from basically
the bottom of the reef

00:06:17.443 --> 00:06:19.145
all the way to the surface,

00:06:19.145 --> 00:06:22.248
sometimes 70, 80 feet high.

00:06:22.248 --> 00:06:23.382
Look at this.

00:06:23.382 --> 00:06:25.351
And here's Jennifer on the side

00:06:25.351 --> 00:06:28.087
of one of these towers.

00:06:28.988 --> 00:06:31.791
The first time we
landed on this sea mount,

00:06:31.791 --> 00:06:36.362
called Joelles,
it was raining fish.

00:06:36.362 --> 00:06:39.431
Jennifer Hayes: They were
isolated, they were unfound,

00:06:39.431 --> 00:06:41.200
they were untouched.

00:06:41.200 --> 00:06:45.138
And they were de facto
marine protected areas.

00:06:45.138 --> 00:06:46.872
They just had no sense of humans

00:06:46.872 --> 00:06:49.809
and one of the scariest things

00:06:49.809 --> 00:06:52.812
and in-your-face
conservation I have ever seen

00:06:52.812 --> 00:06:55.815
was a group of fishermen
in a single boat,

00:06:55.815 --> 00:06:57.683
what they call a banana boat

00:06:57.683 --> 00:07:00.553
and they had found
Joelles reef

00:07:00.553 --> 00:07:01.787
and they had anchored on it

00:07:01.987 --> 00:07:03.456
and they had been on
it all night fishing.

00:07:03.589 --> 00:07:05.057
And the minute they
saw our boat coming,

00:07:05.057 --> 00:07:08.560
they cut their line
and they sped off.

00:07:09.028 --> 00:07:10.830
And it turns out
when we went down,

00:07:10.830 --> 00:07:14.967
all we found were
hooks and fishing line,

00:07:15.301 --> 00:07:18.404
and half or more of
the fish were gone.

00:07:18.404 --> 00:07:20.306
All of the pinjalo snappers.

00:07:20.306 --> 00:07:24.210
Every pinjalo snapper was gone.

00:07:24.210 --> 00:07:27.213
This is one night
on one small piece

00:07:27.213 --> 00:07:30.216
of real estate in the
ocean that was wiped out.

00:07:30.216 --> 00:07:31.750
And the next day when we were

00:07:31.750 --> 00:07:35.588
in the Kimbe Bay market
there were the pinjalos.

00:07:35.588 --> 00:07:37.390
And it shows you how fragile,

00:07:37.390 --> 00:07:40.826
first off it shows us how
marine protected areas

00:07:40.826 --> 00:07:42.862
work and function
and then it shows us

00:07:42.862 --> 00:07:45.798
how vulnerable these places are.

00:07:48.634 --> 00:07:50.769
David: There's small
things on this reef.

00:07:50.769 --> 00:07:54.006
I have to tell you,
anemones and clownfish,

00:07:54.006 --> 00:07:56.842
it's one of the most beautiful
friendships in the sea.

00:07:56.842 --> 00:08:00.312
The anemones protect
the clownfish's eggs,

00:08:00.312 --> 00:08:02.348
protect the clownfish at night

00:08:02.348 --> 00:08:03.482
with its stinging tentacles.

00:08:03.682 --> 00:08:04.650
The clownfish
protects the anemones

00:08:05.117 --> 00:08:07.286
from being nibbled to
death by butterfly fish.

00:08:07.286 --> 00:08:09.521
But Joelles has this
wonderful collection

00:08:09.521 --> 00:08:11.256
of anemones and
toward the evening

00:08:11.256 --> 00:08:12.824
they ball up like this

00:08:12.824 --> 00:08:15.895
and the clownfish begin to
burrow in their stomachs.

00:08:16.162 --> 00:08:19.631
I also managed to
photograph spawning.

00:08:19.631 --> 00:08:21.800
Here are the big
female clownfish.

00:08:21.800 --> 00:08:23.902
And the female is
the dominant partner

00:08:23.902 --> 00:08:25.104
in this relationship.

00:08:25.104 --> 00:08:27.573
If the female dies,
the largest male

00:08:27.573 --> 00:08:30.008
turns into a female and
begins to produce eggs.

00:08:30.008 --> 00:08:31.544
They're producing
eggs right now.

00:08:31.544 --> 00:08:34.247
And that purple curtain
in the background

00:08:34.247 --> 00:08:36.148
is the side of the anemone.

00:08:37.282 --> 00:08:40.253
We dove with sharks.

00:08:41.020 --> 00:08:46.858
(ocean waves)

00:08:47.659 --> 00:08:51.531
♪ (ambient chime music) ♪

00:09:38.143 --> 00:09:41.948
♪ (ambient chime
music continues) ♪

00:09:52.591 --> 00:09:56.362
We were amazed and shocked

00:09:56.362 --> 00:10:01.066
and pleased to see
sharks in Kimbe Bay.

00:10:01.066 --> 00:10:03.268
They would meet you when
you rolled off the boat

00:10:03.268 --> 00:10:05.904
and you were like,
"This is the way

00:10:05.904 --> 00:10:08.140
it is supposed to be."

00:10:08.140 --> 00:10:10.175
So it was just
another indicator,

00:10:10.175 --> 00:10:15.013
another symbol that
these reefs had survived

00:10:15.013 --> 00:10:18.350
where other reefs throughout
the Coral Triangle

00:10:18.350 --> 00:10:20.720
had not done as well.

00:10:23.889 --> 00:10:27.626
David: We dove on a place
called Father's Reef

00:10:27.626 --> 00:10:30.062
and we met a hawksbill turtle.

00:10:30.062 --> 00:10:32.297
And she met us on every dive.

00:10:32.297 --> 00:10:35.300
We could swim with her
as she made her rounds

00:10:35.300 --> 00:10:39.638
past schools of barracudas
and schools of bat-fish.

00:10:39.638 --> 00:10:41.873
I love this picture
because it looks

00:10:41.873 --> 00:10:44.210
like the turtle is flying.

00:10:44.744 --> 00:10:48.381
And then she'd do
this amazing thing:

00:10:48.381 --> 00:10:49.849
instead of going to the surface

00:10:49.849 --> 00:10:51.917
and going back down to
another piece of bottom,

00:10:51.917 --> 00:10:54.853
she would come and she
would rest on our tanks.

00:10:54.853 --> 00:10:57.656
And she would do this, she
would take her flippers

00:10:57.656 --> 00:10:58.891
and put her flippers
around the tank

00:10:58.891 --> 00:11:00.793
and rest there.

00:11:01.727 --> 00:11:03.895
Jennifer: It was wonderful,
she really was magic.

00:11:03.895 --> 00:11:05.464
She met us on every dive

00:11:05.464 --> 00:11:07.499
and she would follow you
and when she was tired

00:11:07.499 --> 00:11:08.533
she would rest on you.

00:11:08.533 --> 00:11:09.668
And it was a magic moment.

00:11:09.868 --> 00:11:13.405
But it was also a
terrifying moment

00:11:13.405 --> 00:11:16.375
in terms of that makes
this particular animal

00:11:16.375 --> 00:11:17.843
very vulnerable.

00:11:17.843 --> 00:11:20.479
The local fishermen
there, they fish the reefs

00:11:20.479 --> 00:11:22.948
that they can find and
they harvest anything

00:11:22.948 --> 00:11:24.583
they can find on the reefs,

00:11:24.583 --> 00:11:27.319
from reef fish to turtles.

00:11:27.319 --> 00:11:30.289
And we would be diving,
a local banana boat

00:11:30.289 --> 00:11:33.058
comes up and with
a group of people,

00:11:33.058 --> 00:11:36.195
the young man swims
down the turtle.

00:11:36.195 --> 00:11:37.896
"How much, how much, how much?

00:11:37.896 --> 00:11:38.897
You buy, you buy, you buy.

00:11:38.897 --> 00:11:40.166
Would you like to buy?"

00:11:40.299 --> 00:11:43.868
Your gut inclination is
for a handful of dollars

00:11:43.868 --> 00:11:45.003
is to buy that turtle,

00:11:45.137 --> 00:11:46.705
take it to the next
coral sea mount

00:11:46.705 --> 00:11:48.006
and let it go.

00:11:48.006 --> 00:11:49.475
But you can't do that

00:11:49.475 --> 00:11:52.178
because you're setting
up a trade, an economy.

00:11:52.178 --> 00:11:53.845
They'll go catch another turtle

00:11:53.845 --> 00:11:55.214
and they'll come
back to you again.

00:11:55.214 --> 00:11:58.049
Or they'll go catch
the same turtle

00:11:58.049 --> 00:12:00.319
and bring it back to you.

00:12:03.488 --> 00:12:05.958
We were in a tiny empire.

00:12:05.958 --> 00:12:08.393
A perfect, tiny coral empire.

00:12:08.393 --> 00:12:12.197
And we needed, we
needed to have an image

00:12:12.197 --> 00:12:13.332
of coral.

00:12:13.332 --> 00:12:14.934
A panorama.

00:12:14.934 --> 00:12:18.103
A shot that said, "This
is this coral world."

00:12:18.103 --> 00:12:21.674
Built of tiny polyps,
beautiful in existence,

00:12:21.674 --> 00:12:22.874
city in the sea.

00:12:23.275 --> 00:12:25.711
This picture isn't
the one we wanted.

00:12:26.478 --> 00:12:29.749
David: And we kept looking
and we kept searching.

00:12:31.083 --> 00:12:33.084 line:0%
David:
A place called an Ann-Sofie.

00:12:33.084 --> 00:12:34.687
It's a group of
islands at the tip

00:12:34.687 --> 00:12:36.788
of the Williamez Peninsula.

00:12:36.788 --> 00:12:38.490
And there's one little island,

00:12:38.490 --> 00:12:39.925
it's not even an island,

00:12:39.925 --> 00:12:41.693
it's an island with a
bunch of trees on it

00:12:41.693 --> 00:12:44.129
and sort of a lone palm tree.

00:12:44.129 --> 00:12:46.999
And it has in one corner of it,

00:12:46.999 --> 00:12:49.434
a field in very,
very shallow water.

00:12:49.434 --> 00:12:52.437
David: In less than a foot
there is a field

00:12:52.437 --> 00:12:56.474
of beautiful purple-laced
coral intermingled

00:12:56.474 --> 00:13:01.413
with a cropper coral
and stagnant coral.

00:13:01.413 --> 00:13:03.449
David:
It's absolutely beautiful.

00:13:03.449 --> 00:13:05.985
And we worked there
and photographed

00:13:05.985 --> 00:13:08.186
David: a picture half and
half out of the water.

00:13:08.186 --> 00:13:10.356
One of the things I
particularly liked to do.

00:13:10.356 --> 00:13:13.125
And as we were working
a father and son came up

00:13:13.125 --> 00:13:14.593
in a dugout, they
were fishing there.

00:13:14.593 --> 00:13:16.595
We give them lunch later on.

00:13:17.129 --> 00:13:20.199
(indistinct chatter)

00:13:22.367 --> 00:13:25.504
Jennifer: We'll see
Anton and his papa again.

