in the<i> National
 Geographic magazine</i>

00:14:28.968 --> 00:14:31.136
on the gulf of St. Lawrence.

00:14:31.136 --> 00:14:34.006
Jennifer:
It was a very challenging story

00:14:34.006 --> 00:14:37.176
but very near and
dear to our hearts.

00:14:37.176 --> 00:14:39.444
We live on the
St. Lawrence river

00:14:39.444 --> 00:14:42.013
in a region called
The Thousand Islands.

00:14:42.013 --> 00:14:44.282
This is our neighborhood.

00:14:44.282 --> 00:14:45.617
David: Yeah, this is not
our house, incidentally.

00:14:45.784 --> 00:14:48.086
Jennifer: This is, people
ask us all the time.

00:14:48.086 --> 00:14:52.524
We live in an area
surrounded by 1,800 islands,

00:14:52.524 --> 00:14:56.828
storybook castles and
an amazing creature

00:14:56.828 --> 00:14:58.464
Jennifer: called the sturgeon.

00:14:58.464 --> 00:15:01.566
There are 27 species of
sturgeon in the world.

00:15:01.566 --> 00:15:04.036
They're all in the
northern hemisphere.

00:15:04.036 --> 00:15:07.940
All 27 of them are
falling flat on their face

00:15:07.940 --> 00:15:09.674
because they are long-lived;

00:15:09.674 --> 00:15:13.445
they live to be over
100, sometimes 200.

00:15:13.445 --> 00:15:16.848
Get this: they don't
spawn until they're

00:15:16.848 --> 00:15:20.185
about 25 years old.

00:15:20.185 --> 00:15:22.554
And then, not even
every year after that.

00:15:22.554 --> 00:15:23.889
it's every five years.

00:15:23.889 --> 00:15:26.725
So 25, 30, 35 and you can see,

00:15:26.725 --> 00:15:29.228
all of a sudden, when
you put the pressure

00:15:29.228 --> 00:15:31.496
of fisheries on a
species like this,

00:15:31.496 --> 00:15:33.365
Jennifer: how these stocks
are collapsing.

00:15:33.365 --> 00:15:36.234
And these sturgeon are very shy,

00:15:36.234 --> 00:15:37.703
they like deep water,

00:15:37.703 --> 00:15:40.139
they're very rare to see
underwater most of the year,

00:15:40.139 --> 00:15:43.342
except for one week
in the month of June,

00:15:43.342 --> 00:15:45.277
thousands of them
gather and they meet

00:15:45.277 --> 00:15:47.112
on these spawning beds.

00:15:47.112 --> 00:15:50.348
This particular type of
rock, in very fast water.

00:15:50.348 --> 00:15:53.152
This water is like
washing machine water,

00:15:53.152 --> 00:15:56.121
it is about a four knot current.

00:15:56.121 --> 00:15:59.123
Right now I am behind
a big giant rock

00:15:59.123 --> 00:16:01.260
trying to stay out
of the current.

00:16:01.260 --> 00:16:04.296
And these girls, these are
all girls waiting to spawn,

00:16:04.296 --> 00:16:06.131
just ignoring me because they're

00:16:06.131 --> 00:16:07.499
all pumped up on hormones.

00:16:07.732 --> 00:16:10.235
Any other time of the year
I couldn't get near them.

00:16:10.235 --> 00:16:12.370
Jennifer: And the sturgeon
are a unique fish.

00:16:12.370 --> 00:16:15.507
They are so ugly, I
think they're beautiful.

00:16:15.507 --> 00:16:17.976
I would marry a sturgeon if
I could marry a sturgeon.

00:16:17.976 --> 00:16:20.712
-I married a sturgeon.
-See their mouth and barbules.

00:16:20.712 --> 00:16:23.582
-You did marry a sturgeon.
-I married a sturgeon.

00:16:23.582 --> 00:16:24.516
Oh my God, you did.

00:16:24.750 --> 00:16:27.686
These barbules, see
these four things.

00:16:27.686 --> 00:16:29.287
Those are called barbules

00:16:29.287 --> 00:16:31.390
and they have all these
chemosensory ability

00:16:31.390 --> 00:16:33.258
and they go along the bottom

00:16:33.258 --> 00:16:34.393
and they brush past something

00:16:34.393 --> 00:16:36.128
and they say, "I can eat that."

00:16:36.128 --> 00:16:37.997
And womp! Down
comes its mouth.

00:16:37.997 --> 00:16:40.232
Have you ever seen
a mouth like that?

00:16:40.232 --> 00:16:42.100
(audience awes)

00:16:42.767 --> 00:16:45.804
David: Past Quebec the
river becomes an estuary.

00:16:45.804 --> 00:16:49.341
And a little past
there the Saginaw River

00:16:49.341 --> 00:16:52.611
joins the St. Lawrence
and there's a population

00:16:52.611 --> 00:16:54.013
David: of beluga whales.

00:16:54.013 --> 00:16:55.247
Beluga whales are
the white whales,

00:16:55.247 --> 00:16:56.147
the canary whales.

00:16:56.281 --> 00:16:57.315
They sing and they burble

00:16:57.315 --> 00:16:59.151
and they make a lot of noise.

00:16:59.151 --> 00:17:00.919
And this guy came right up to me

00:17:00.919 --> 00:17:02.921
and kind of blew me a kiss,

00:17:02.921 --> 00:17:04.255
it went bloop!

00:17:04.255 --> 00:17:05.991
A little bubble came out.

00:17:05.991 --> 00:17:06.758
(audience laughter)

00:17:07.592 --> 00:17:10.062
David: And then the whale did
this marvelous thing.

00:17:10.062 --> 00:17:11.296
He tried to eat the camera.

00:17:11.296 --> 00:17:14.099
(audience laughter)

00:17:15.700 --> 00:17:18.637
Jennifer: There used to
be 10,000 beluga whales

00:17:18.637 --> 00:17:19.972
in the St. Lawrence.

00:17:19.972 --> 00:17:21.506
It can support up to 10,000.

00:17:21.506 --> 00:17:24.276
And then they were
fished; they were killed,

00:17:24.276 --> 00:17:26.711
because all the fishermen
thought that they

00:17:26.711 --> 00:17:28.514
were competing for fish
so they were slaughtered.

00:17:28.514 --> 00:17:30.982
And then it got down to
a handful of thousand.

00:17:30.982 --> 00:17:34.786
And just weeks ago a
report came out and said,

00:17:34.786 --> 00:17:38.423
"No, no, no, no. We
are down to 800."

00:17:38.423 --> 00:17:39.557
And what is happening

00:17:39.657 --> 00:17:41.994
is there's high
infant mortality.

00:17:41.994 --> 00:17:44.196
The problem is they
don't know what

00:17:44.196 --> 00:17:46.331
is causing the infant mortality.

00:17:46.331 --> 00:17:48.467
So the Department of Fisheries

00:17:48.467 --> 00:17:49.601
and the Canadian scientists

00:17:49.768 --> 00:17:52.471
are now in scramble
and panic mode

00:17:52.471 --> 00:17:57.342
to figure out how to
preserve these 800 belugas.

00:17:57.342 --> 00:17:59.511
They are precious
and they are almost

00:17:59.511 --> 00:18:02.381
a symbol of the St. Lawrence.

00:18:04.749 --> 00:18:06.184
David: And don't forget,

00:18:06.184 --> 00:18:09.087
we are in French
Canada, French Canada.

00:18:09.087 --> 00:18:11.222
And I photographed crabs.

00:18:11.456 --> 00:18:12.890
David: Crabs mating.

00:18:13.024 --> 00:18:16.228
(French accent) In French Canada
it is not just mating

00:18:16.228 --> 00:18:18.730
but is<i> L'Amour</i> ; love.

00:18:18.730 --> 00:18:19.397
(audience laughter)

00:18:19.597 --> 00:18:21.232
They do this for weeks and weeks

00:18:21.232 --> 00:18:23.035
at a time, you know.

00:18:23.035 --> 00:18:25.604
(David laughing)

00:18:25.604 --> 00:18:26.938
(speaking foreign language)

00:18:27.405 --> 00:18:32.577
<i> Après, après l'sex, after
 l'sex comes l'cigarette.</i>

00:18:32.978 --> 00:18:35.814
(audience laughing)

00:18:36.348 --> 00:18:38.584
Jennifer: Gimme that.

00:18:40.218 --> 00:18:41.886
Oh my God.

00:18:42.687 --> 00:18:45.356
Jennifer: The gulf of
St. Lawrence

00:18:45.356 --> 00:18:47.792
freezes in the winter time

00:18:47.792 --> 00:18:51.563
and it becomes the
world of the harp seal.

00:18:51.563 --> 00:18:54.232
They are nursed by their mothers

00:18:54.232 --> 00:18:56.968
for about 12 days.

00:18:56.968 --> 00:18:58.136
Then they're abandoned,

00:18:58.337 --> 00:19:00.071
they're left on the
ice to figure out

00:19:00.071 --> 00:19:02.874
how to become a harp seal.

00:19:02.874 --> 00:19:05.243
How to feed, how to swim,

00:19:05.243 --> 00:19:08.546
how to do anything
and everything.

00:19:09.680 --> 00:19:12.483
Jennifer: In 2011,
when this picture was made,

00:19:12.483 --> 00:19:15.686
it took us three days by
boat to get to the ice.

00:19:15.686 --> 00:19:19.824
It kept moving, there was
so little ice in the gulf.

00:19:19.824 --> 00:19:23.027
And we located a patch
and a field of ice

00:19:23.027 --> 00:19:25.530
and it had 10,000 seals.

00:19:25.530 --> 00:19:29.168
And this is what 10,000
seals begins to look like.

00:19:30.735 --> 00:19:34.239
And we can give you an
idea of what it's like

00:19:34.239 --> 00:19:36.508
in the world of the harp seal.

00:19:37.376 --> 00:19:39.878
That's its umbilical there.

00:19:41.012 --> 00:19:42.714
A newborn.

00:19:43.381 --> 00:19:45.918
Three days old, with
the mother in the back.

00:19:48.419 --> 00:19:50.455
(baby seal crying out)

00:19:57.261 --> 00:19:59.798
A very nervous mother.

00:20:02.834 --> 00:20:04.803
(baby seal cries)

00:20:14.379 --> 00:20:16.949
Still a very nervous mother.

00:20:26.023 --> 00:20:27.992
To me, they're one of the
most beautiful creatures

00:20:27.992 --> 00:20:29.094
on the planet.

00:20:29.261 --> 00:20:30.228
For the first 12
days of their life,

00:20:30.529 --> 00:20:31.930
when they're called
the white coats,

00:20:31.930 --> 00:20:35.200
they look almost
like a stuffed toy.

00:20:35.200 --> 00:20:37.202
(audience oohs and awes)

00:20:37.469 --> 00:20:41.439
And once in a while
you'll see a blind one.

00:20:41.439 --> 00:20:43.475
And it's very sad because
they'll come up to you,

00:20:43.475 --> 00:20:45.143
thinking you're their mother.

00:20:45.143 --> 00:20:46.745
They're desperate,

00:20:47.245 --> 00:20:49.047
without that particular sensory.

00:20:49.047 --> 00:20:52.684
And after 12 to 15
days they begin to molt

00:20:52.684 --> 00:20:54.919
and they begin to
shed their white coat

00:20:54.919 --> 00:20:56.354
and become what's
called a beater.

00:20:56.521 --> 00:20:59.090
And at this point
they are also eligible

00:20:59.090 --> 00:21:00.759
to enter the hunt.

00:21:00.759 --> 00:21:03.261
The Canadian seal
hunt still goes on.

00:21:03.261 --> 00:21:04.596
There's a lower quota

00:21:04.596 --> 00:21:06.398
and they cannot
take the white coats

00:21:06.398 --> 00:21:08.399
but they can take the beaters.

00:21:08.399 --> 00:21:11.269
Jennifer: And David has found
a beater.

00:21:11.737 --> 00:21:16.374
And I find a pup
peering through the ice,

00:21:16.374 --> 00:21:18.443
looking for his mom.

00:21:19.110 --> 00:21:21.112
He sees me, he's like, "No."

00:21:21.112 --> 00:21:23.715
(audience laughs)

00:21:24.215 --> 00:21:25.917
Mom is behind me,

00:21:25.917 --> 00:21:30.155
going a little crazy now
because I'm between her

00:21:30.155 --> 00:21:31.689
and her pup.

00:21:32.190 --> 00:21:35.259
She rushes past me
and she greets her pup

00:21:35.259 --> 00:21:37.929
and she coaxes him
into the water.

00:21:37.929 --> 00:21:41.099
They meet with this
underwater nose-to-nose,

00:21:41.099 --> 00:21:42.867
I call it a kiss of recognition.
(kissing sound)

00:21:42.867 --> 00:21:44.969
It's like smooch,
are you my mom?

00:21:44.969 --> 00:21:48.373
Are you my pup or
are you an impostor?

00:21:48.373 --> 00:21:51.476
And while we're swimming
the pup is very curious.

00:21:51.476 --> 00:21:52.777
What are you? Who are you?

00:21:52.777 --> 00:21:54.579
What's going on? Who are you?

00:21:54.579 --> 00:21:57.416
And he would try
to swim towards me,

00:21:57.416 --> 00:21:58.583
he would get a little close

00:21:58.583 --> 00:22:00.284
and the mother would come up

00:22:00.284 --> 00:22:02.453
and literally hold
him down, "No."

00:22:02.820 --> 00:22:06.624
And eventually she allowed
him to get a little closer

00:22:06.624 --> 00:22:08.593
and he gets so close
and he scrabbles.

00:22:08.593 --> 00:22:10.695
He begins to climb up on my--

00:22:10.695 --> 00:22:13.865
Here you come be the
seal, you're there.

00:22:13.865 --> 00:22:16.468
-So he begins to do this.
-I'm the seal.

00:22:16.468 --> 00:22:19.070
And then he climbs up onto me,

00:22:19.070 --> 00:22:21.106
I'm the raft, I'm the ice.

00:22:21.106 --> 00:22:26.043
And now he's on my
chest, he's tired

00:22:26.043 --> 00:22:27.545
and he's on my chest.

00:22:27.545 --> 00:22:30.882
And he's nosing my mask
like he did his mom.

00:22:30.882 --> 00:22:33.918
Like I'm the impostor,
I am the impostor.

00:22:33.918 --> 00:22:35.453
Jennifer: We swim along
and we move

00:22:35.453 --> 00:22:36.922
into this very open water.

00:22:36.922 --> 00:22:40.458
Now we're resting,
we're all stopped.

00:22:40.458 --> 00:22:43.495
Then something
nips my left ankle,

00:22:43.495 --> 00:22:45.430
then something nips
my right ankle.

00:22:45.430 --> 00:22:48.399
And I look down and
there's 30 or 40

00:22:48.399 --> 00:22:53.105
male harp seals
circling below me.

00:22:54.205 --> 00:22:57.609
A male comes up over my back,

00:22:57.609 --> 00:22:59.043
pushes me down,

00:22:59.310 --> 00:23:02.280
his penis gets caught in my mask
(audience laughs with disgust)

00:23:02.280 --> 00:23:05.250
taking it off with him.

00:23:05.950 --> 00:23:09.120
The mask drops, we're
in 3,000 feet of water.

00:23:09.454 --> 00:23:11.456
I see it, I grab it.

00:23:11.456 --> 00:23:13.391
Got my camera here

00:23:13.391 --> 00:23:16.194
and the male is
going down below me

00:23:16.194 --> 00:23:19.164
and the female sweeps past

00:23:19.164 --> 00:23:20.565
and she goes down and the mother

00:23:20.565 --> 00:23:23.401
is beating the crap
out of this male.

00:23:23.401 --> 00:23:26.404
(audience laughs and applauds)

00:23:26.404 --> 00:23:28.873
The mother surfaces,

00:23:28.873 --> 00:23:32.010
she surfaces and she's
grunting and snorting

00:23:32.010 --> 00:23:32.577
(heaving noise)

00:23:33.144 --> 00:23:35.046
and she comes back
and I'm thinking,

00:23:35.046 --> 00:23:37.648
"I'm not sure what's
going to happen now."

00:23:37.648 --> 00:23:41.052
But she comes back
and she uses her head

00:23:41.052 --> 00:23:43.654
and her flipper
and her entire body

00:23:43.654 --> 00:23:46.825
and she kind of
scoops up her pup.

00:23:46.825 --> 00:23:48.259
Kind of using
everything she's got.

00:23:48.259 --> 00:23:50.562
And she kind of gets
him in front of her.

00:23:50.762 --> 00:23:54.232
And then she uses her
flipper, her nose,

00:23:54.232 --> 00:23:56.701
her body and she scoops me up.

00:23:56.701 --> 00:23:59.237
(audience laughs)

00:23:59.671 --> 00:24:01.139
-Now...
-Super mom.

00:24:01.139 --> 00:24:03.841
The pup and
I were being propelled.

00:24:03.841 --> 00:24:06.077
Herded through the water,

00:24:06.077 --> 00:24:07.578
out of this open
area where we had

00:24:07.578 --> 00:24:09.080
all the males beneath us.

00:24:09.080 --> 00:24:12.750
I ducked underneath and
I watched the mother

00:24:12.750 --> 00:24:13.952
and the pup disappear.

00:24:13.952 --> 00:24:16.320
I'm pumped up on adrenaline,

00:24:16.320 --> 00:24:17.622
I'm ecstatic, I'm excited,

00:24:17.622 --> 00:24:19.190
I go to the edge of the ice

00:24:19.190 --> 00:24:20.558
and I throw my camera up.

00:24:20.558 --> 00:24:22.561
And I'm taking
off my weight belt

00:24:22.561 --> 00:24:24.262
and just as I'm taking
off my weight belt,

00:24:24.262 --> 00:24:27.699
right at the edge of
the ice a male harp seal

00:24:27.699 --> 00:24:30.468
comes under the edge of the ice

00:24:30.468 --> 00:24:33.071
and he bites me
square in the groin.

00:24:34.472 --> 00:24:35.606
And he lets go.

00:24:35.940 --> 00:24:39.543
And then he bites me
square in the thigh.

00:24:39.810 --> 00:24:41.212
Wonk! And he lets go.

00:24:41.212 --> 00:24:45.183
And I have a very,
very memorable scar

00:24:45.183 --> 00:24:46.284
from all of that.

00:24:46.451 --> 00:24:49.820
But it's not the scar
and it's not the male

00:24:49.820 --> 00:24:53.191
that I would ever or
want to or will dwell on.

00:24:53.458 --> 00:24:59.130
It is the female
and her reaction.

00:24:59.130 --> 00:25:01.399
Jennifer: And I will say
the world of the harp seal

00:25:01.399 --> 00:25:03.301
has been a changing world.

00:25:03.301 --> 00:25:05.836
David and I were on
our way back to shore,

00:25:05.836 --> 00:25:10.208
a storm came up and the
ice was so bad, so weak,

00:25:10.208 --> 00:25:11.109
(Jennifer: deep breath in)

00:25:11.309 --> 00:25:13.178
that when the
storm came through,

00:25:13.178 --> 00:25:17.882
it wrecked the sea ice
and 10,000 pups perished.

00:25:17.882 --> 00:25:19.384
Every one of them died.

00:25:19.384 --> 00:25:24.422
They had 100 percent
mortality of the gulf seals

00:25:24.422 --> 00:25:26.091
in that particular year.

00:25:26.091 --> 00:25:30.128
This past year in 2014
was a big ice year.

00:25:30.128 --> 00:25:32.897
That's a relief, we
had a relief year,

00:25:32.897 --> 00:25:35.333
because we had had three to four

00:25:35.333 --> 00:25:38.837
almost full-on 100
percent mortality years.

00:25:38.837 --> 00:25:44.809
So it is a shifting world
for our climate there.

00:25:44.809 --> 00:25:47.379
And what I want to close
on is David and I go back

00:25:47.379 --> 00:25:48.546
every year now.

00:25:48.680 --> 00:25:52.484
We have become
addicted to the ice.

00:25:52.484 --> 00:25:55.953
-We feel--
-Extraordinary place.

00:25:55.953 --> 00:25:58.323
We go back every year

00:25:58.323 --> 00:26:00.758
and what we're trying to do

00:26:00.758 --> 00:26:02.460
is create a shifting paradigm

00:26:02.460 --> 00:26:07.065
away from hunting into
a model of ecotourism.

00:26:07.065 --> 00:26:09.134
Now we can take some people up

00:26:09.134 --> 00:26:10.067
and we take a week

00:26:10.167 --> 00:26:11.569
out of the harp
seal hunting boat.

00:26:11.702 --> 00:26:13.337
We buy a week, we
buy another week,

00:26:13.337 --> 00:26:14.706
we buy another week.

00:26:14.839 --> 00:26:17.809
And hopefully we'll show
them a different economy.

00:26:17.809 --> 00:26:19.844
An ecotourism-based economy

00:26:19.844 --> 00:26:22.747
where we can take the
pressure off the hunting.

00:26:23.048 --> 00:26:26.684
And with that I would like
to thank you all for coming.

00:26:26.684 --> 00:26:29.020
You've been
an incredible audience.

00:26:29.020 --> 00:26:31.856
(applause)

